 to ‘see now, buy now’: a genealogy of the fashion show live stream -- tChapter 11. Documenting fashion in the era of Instagram: a critical reading of Asri Bendacha’s Follow Me and Chiara Ferragni’s Unposted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffers the first edited collection with an explicit documentary focus on fashion icons, events, cultures and industriesInvestigates the bearings of the documentary image and its visual politics in relation to fashionPushes forward new understandings of how different media and platforms, such as documentary feature films, television factual programmes, online videos, fashion exhibitions, edutainment and industrial films, interrogate ‘the real’ in relation to fashionConsiders a wide range of both contemporary and historical case studies, including analysis of fashion documentaries, fashion-series on television and online videos, including Queer Eye (2018), Follow Me (2017), Bill Cunningham New York (2010), and McQueen (2018)Includes two expanding interviews, one with Alexandra Palmer, senior fashion curator at Royal Ontario Museum, Toronto, and one with Lorna Tucker, director of Westwood: Punk, Icon, Activists (2018)Feuds within fashion houses, megalomaniacs and photoshoot nightmares – fashion and drama have been a perfect match for decades. Over the past ten years, we have witnessed a boom of documentaries about fashion magazine editors, fashion and media politics and the history of fashion houses.How and why did fashion documentaries and non-fiction media become so popular? Documenting Fashion explores and reassesses the role of documentary media by tracing its history in shaping our understanding of fashion across multiple platforms and different national contexts, including industrial films, newsreels, TV shows, documentary films, digital media and photography. The essays in this collection underpin and profile a scholarly space in which a dialogue between fashion and documentary studies can evolve by drawing from different methodologies and approaches, such as media and cultural studies, ethnography, archival and museum studies, gender studies, marketing and public relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCelebrities in mass media. 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aFashion in mass media. 0aFashion in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aDESIGN / Fashion & Accessories.2bisacsh1 aAffuso, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjörkin, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaffaro, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaoduro, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaoduro, Elena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDyer, Jihane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalliday, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehnert, Sigrun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakama, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPedroni, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRitzenhoff, Karen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUlfsdotter, Boel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUlfsdotter, Boel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2023z9783111318097oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2023 Englishz978311131903208iTitle is part of eBook packa